{{Orphan|date=December 2012}} {{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Al-Haramain v. Obama |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=June 1, |ArgueYear=2012 |DecideDate=August 7, |DecideYear=2012 |FullName=[[Al-Haramain Islamic Foundation]], et al v. [[Barack Obama]], et al |Citations=690 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/806130/al-haramain-islamic-foundation-v-barack-obama/ 1089] |Prior=''Al-Haramain v. Bush'', 507 F.3d [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1434598/al-haramain-islamic-foundation-inc-v-bush/ 1190] (9th Cir. 2007) |Subsequent= |Holding= |Judges=[[Harry Pregerson]], [[Michael Daly Hawkins]], [[M. Margaret McKeown]] |Majority=McKeown |JoinMajority=a unanimous court |LawsApplied= }} '''''Al-Haramain v. Obama''''', 690 [[Federal Reporter|F.3d]] 1089 (9th Cir. 2012)<ref name="Appeal">{{cite court |litigants=Al-Haramain v. Obama |vol=690 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1089 |pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2012 |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/806130/al-haramain-islamic-foundation-v-barack-obama/ |accessdate=2017-11-03 |quote=}}</ref> was a case before the [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California|U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California]] filed 28 February 2006 by the [[al-Haramain Foundation]] and others concerning the [[NSA warrantless surveillance controversy]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Islamic charity sues to shut down NSA warrantless wiretapping program |last=Pantesco |first=Joshua |date=February 28, 2006 |publisher=[[JURIST]] ([[University of Pittsburgh School of Law]]) |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2006/02/islamic-charity-sues-to-shut-down-nsa.php |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111004050/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2006/02/islamic-charity-sues-to-shut-down-nsa.php |archivedate=January 11, 2011 }}</ref> The case withstood retroactive changes brought by the Congressional response to the NSA warrantless surveillance program.<ref>{{cite web | title= Judge Tosses Warrantless Wiretap Cases | first= Martin | last= Kaste | date= June 4, 2009 | publisher= [[National Public Radio]] | url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=104922405 }}</ref>
On March 31, 2010, Chief Judge [[Vaughn R. Walker]] granted partial [[summary judgment]] in favor of the [[plaintiff]]s,<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal judge rules for Islamic charity in NSA wiretapping case |last=Glenn |first=Matt |date=April 1, 2010 |publisher=[[JURIST]] ([[University of Pittsburgh School of Law]]) |url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2010/04/federal-judge-rules-for-islamic-charity.php |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111004015/http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2010/04/federal-judge-rules-for-islamic-charity.php |archivedate=January 11, 2011 }}</ref> and on 21 December awarded $2.5 million in attorneys' fees and about $41,000 to two of the three plaintiffs.<ref>{{cite news | title= Walker Awards $41K Damages, $2.5 Million Fee in Wiretap Case | publisher= The Recorder | url= http://www.law.com/jsp/ca/PubArticleCA.jsp?id=1202476555404 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.courthousenews.com/2010/12/21/obama.pdf In Re National Security Agency Telecommunications Records], Al-Haramain et. al v. Obama et. al, [[United States District Court for the Northern District of California|U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California]]</ref>
The district court was reversed and the case was subsequently dismissed by [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit|Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals]] on August 7, 2012.<ref name="Appeal"/>
