"'''For a Swarm of Bees'''" is an [[Anglo-Saxon Metrical Charms|Anglo-Saxon metrical charm]] that was intended for use in keeping [[Western honey bee|honey bee]]s from [[Swarming (honey bee)|swarming]]. The text was discovered by [[John Mitchell Kemble]] in the 19th century.{{sfnp|Kemble|1876|pp=403-404}} The charm is named for its opening words, "''{{lang|ang|wiþ ymbe}}''", meaning "against (or towards) a swarm of bees".{{sfnp|Bosworth|1889}}

In the most often studied portion, towards the end of the text where the charm itself is located, the bees are referred to as ''{{lang|ang|sigewif}}'', "victory-women". The word has been associated by Kemble,{{sfnp|Kemble|1876|pp=403-404}} [[Jacob Grimm]], and other scholars with the notion of [[valkyries]] (Old English ''{{lang|ang|wælcyrian}}''), and "[[shield maiden]]s", hosts of female beings attested in [[Old Norse]] and, to a lesser extent, Old English sources, similar to or identical with the [[Idis (Germanic)|Idis]]e of the [[Merseburg Incantations]].{{sfnp|Davidson|1990|p=63}} Among some recent scholars the term has been theorized as a simple metaphor for the "victorious sword" (the stinging) of the bees.{{sfnp|Greenfield|1996|p=256}}

[[File:Lorscher Bienensegen.jpg|right|thumb|''Lorscher Bienensegen'' manuscript]]
In 1909, the scholar Felix Grendon recorded what he saw as similarities between the charm and the [[Lorsch Bee Blessing]], a manuscript portion of the [[Lorsch Codex]], from the monastery in [[Lorsch]], Germany. Grendon suggested that the two could possibly have a common origin in pre-Christian Germanic culture.{{sfnp|Grendon|1909}}

